defaultDiscretionary Housing Paymentsdefault&#xa0;default6.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultShelter is extremely concerned that Discretionary Housing Payments 
default(DHPs) are being called upon inappropriately to support people with a predictable and clearly defined additional need, when statutory regulations would be better placed to avoid unintended consequences.
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultConcerns with DHPs:defaultThey are discretionarydefault - People cannot guarantee they will receive support, even if their circumstances are those that Ministers had in mind when releasing additional funding.  
defaultThey are short-termdefault –
default 
defaultAlthough guidance does state that indefinite awards can be made if a claimant’
defaults circumstances are unlikely to change
default,
default local authorities are wary of doing this as it makes it harder to budget. Where a shortfall is ongoing and predictable people shouldn’t have to go through repeated applications.
defaultThey are cash-limiteddefault – The allocation
default of DHP given to local councils is cash limited and insufficient to respond to everyone with a shortfall. The need to make the budget last throughout the year can also encourage local authorities not to publicise DHPs or to reject applications earlier in t
defaulthe year in case of a surge in demand later. Local authorities can top-up the DWP allocation by 1.5 times but are legally prohibited from spending anything beyond this. Moreover, many are unable to do so because of pressures on their budgets.  
default&#xa0;
default6.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultI
defaultn the firs
defaultt three months of 2013 th
defaultere was a sharp increase (of 60 per cent
default) in the number of DHP applications 
defaultin local authorities in England from 
default31,562
default (2011/12)
default to
default 
default50,393
default (2012/13)
default. In 2011/12 the average number of DHP applications per local authority was 274, i
defaultt rose to 420 in 2012/13, and just in the first three months of 2013/14 an average of 294 DHP applications have been received per local authority. We therefore do not expect the historic trend of local authorities returning unspent DHP allocations to be re
defaultpeated.
